[1] Measures to regulate the trade and maintenance of wild animals in China
Date: Fri 31 Jan 2020
Source: Xinhuanet News [in Chinese, machine trans., abridged, edited]
http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-01/31/c_1125515239.htm


On 26 Jan 2020, the China Centers for Disease Control and Prevention announced that the new coronavirus was detected in environmental samples from the South China Seafood Market in Wuhan [see item 2]. The virus originated from wild animals sold in the seafood market.

For this reason, the State General Administration of Market Supervision, the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs, and the National Forestry and Grassland Bureau jointly issued a public announcement on the 26th that from now on until the end of the national epidemic, wild animal trading activities are prohibited to cut off the source and transmission of the virus.

On 28 Jan 2020, the State Forestry and Grassland Administration issued the Work Plan on Supervision and Inspection of Strengthening the Implementation and Control of Wildlife Control Measures, requiring local supervisory agencies to implement inspection responsibilities for wildlife trading markets, restaurants, and other places, and for wildlife trading. [There is] supervision and inspection of the clearance and surveillance of wild animal epidemics and the establishment of a daily reporting system.

Hubei, Shanghai, Sichuan, Yunnan, Guangdong, Zhejiang, Jilin, Henan, Inner Mongolia, Jiangsu, Hunan, and other provinces/autonomous regions and municipalities immediately issued policies to urgently suspend wildlife trading.

In addition to banning wildlife trade, some provinces have stopped trading live birds. Hubei, Inner Mongolia, and Henan have banned the sale of live poultry and wild animals. The Henan Provincial Market Supervision Bureau issued a document on 21 Jan 2020, demanding that the sale of live poultry be banned on the market from now on. Operators who still sell live poultry on the market and kill poultry products such as poultry onsite will be ordered to cease operations. Shanghai requires that from 25 Jan to 30 Apr 2020, Shanghai will implement a seasonal suspension of live bird trading. Yunnan province prohibits bamboo rats, tadpoles, and other wild animals that may carry the new coronavirus from being transported, traded, and sold on the market. It also requires strict implementation of the ban on live birds at the local farmers' market.

Jilin, Shandong, Hubei, and other places announced the suspension of all wildlife-related transactions and exhibition activities. The Shaanxi Provincial Forestry Bureau has introduced 10 measures to ensure a safe distance between people and animals. From 22 Jan 2020, Wuhan Zoo, Jiufeng Forest Zoo, and other scenic spots have been closed to the outside world. Breeders disinfect the cages and out-of-house playgrounds in accordance with the established disinfection system every day.

Some regions have policies that prohibit online wildlife trading. Zhejiang province strengthened the monitoring of e-commerce platforms, banned online trading of wild animals, and searched and blocked 32 keywords of wild animals. Shenzhen requires various edible agricultural products wholesale markets, farmer's markets, shopping malls, supermarkets and other trading markets (places) and their internal operators, and various catering service units and e-commerce platform operators are strictly prohibited from trading wild animals and their products. Shanxi Taiyuan Market Supervision and Administration Bureau issued the "Notice on Strengthening the Supervision of Wild Animal Markets." The operators of various farmers' markets, supermarkets, restaurants, and e-commerce platforms in the city are strictly prohibited from trading wild animals and their products in any form and closing live bird trading.

In order to effectively prevent the spread of pneumonia outbreaks of new coronavirus infections, many regions have implemented strict law enforcement to ban wild animal trading venues and block trading channels.

Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region will monitor the business entities that sell wild animals and live poultry and live animals on the internet within the autonomous region. As of the afternoon of 25 Jan 2020, 7 online shops suspected of selling related products have been monitored, involving 7 alliance cities including Hohhot. All products in the 7 shops have, by now, been removed and their websites closed.

On the afternoon of 26 Jan 2020, Zhou Zhenghua, deputy director of the Zhumadian Forestry Public Security Bureau of Henan province, led a team to conduct a one-by-one inspection on Zhumadian's agricultural product market, pet market, flower and bird trading market, and wildlife domestication, breeding, and trading venues. As of 5 p.m. on 27 Jan [2020], Zhumadian had dispatched a total of 11 police cars with more than 50 police officers to investigate more than 30 markets in the city. Due to the publicity in place, no wild animals were found.

Songjiang district of Shanghai issued notices to 3 indoor zoo-type business establishments, including Xingmeng pet, and suspended operations. At present, the monitoring of epidemic diseases is mainly carried out. Daily inspections are carried out at 5 wildlife monitoring stations at or above the municipal level to observe whether there is abnormal behavior of wild animals and whether there are abnormal deaths.

Guangdong province temporarily suspended the application for national administrative protection permits for wildlife hunting, breeding, sale, purchase, utilization, and transportation. Transshipment and trafficking of wild animals is strictly forbidden. As of 27 Jan 2020, the market supervision department inspected a total of 3835 farmers' markets and 8984 live poultry operators and found that there were 8 problems with illegal sales of wild animals, of which 7 completed rectification and filed a case for investigation.

Hunan province has implemented a "one control, 4 prohibitions" measure and sealed off and isolated all wild animals in artificial breeding sites.

In Zhejiang province, a total of 7486 inspection and enforcement officers were dispatched by the market supervision department. They have inspected 2224 farmers' markets, 13 507 households, and 787 malls and supermarkets.

Beijing, Hebei, Chongqing, Shanxi, Ningxia, and other places have initiated joint prevention and control measures to severely investigate and deal with activities such as wildlife trading and transshipment.

[For the detailed additional control/investigation/enforcement activities in other provinces, please refer to the full report (in Chinese) at the source URL. - Mod.AS]

