[The measures undertaken in China to intensify the control upon and even limit the trade in wild animals and their products have been long due; in fact, they have been advocated by China's leading scientists in the field of coronavirus research and their animal reservoir. - Mod.AS]

******
[2] Virus detection in environmental samples from the seafood market
Date: Sun 26 Jan 2020
Source: China's National Microbiology Data Center [in Chinese, machine trans., edited]
https://tinyurl.com/sbbb6ml


A total of 585 samples were collected from 2 batches of South China Seafood City. PCR tests showed that 33 samples were positive for the new coronavirus nucleic acid. The investigation found that the South China Seafood Market was nominally a seafood market but was actually a comprehensive market.

China Daily, 26 Jan 2020 (reporter Wang Xiaodong). A reporter learned today from the China Centers for Disease Control and Prevention that since the outbreak of a new coronavirus, the center's virus disease center has continued to address the virus traceability research and made progress. For the 1st time, from 585 environmental samples from the South China Seafood Market, 33 samples contained novel coronavirus nucleic acids, and the virus was successfully isolated from positive environmental specimens, suggesting that the virus originated from wild animals sold in the South China Seafood Market [see comment].

Most of the early confirmed cases of Wuhan's new coronavirus epidemic came from Wuhan South China Seafood Market. On 31 Dec 2019, according to the requirements of the China Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the selected expert group went to Wuhan to participate in the epidemic prevention and control activities, and in the early morning of 1 Jan 2020, drafted the "Environment Traceability Work Plan." At 8 a.m. on 1 Jan 2020, I went to South China Seafood City to collect 515 environmental samples from case-related merchants and related neighborhoods and transported them to the virus disease laboratory for testing. On 12 Jan 2020, experts from the Institute of Viral Diseases collected an additional 70 specimens of wild animal vendors in the South China Seafood Market and transferred them to the laboratory for testing.

PCR tests showed that 33 samples out of the 585 collected were positive for the new coronavirus nucleic acid. These positive samples were collected from 22 stalls and one garbage truck on the market, of which 93.9% (31/33) positive specimens were distributed in the western part of the South China Seafood Market. The investigation found that the South China Seafood Market was nominally a seafood market but was actually a comprehensive market. There is a wildlife trade in the western part of the South China Seafood Market, especially in the areas near 7th and 8th streets within the western area, where there are many wildlife dealers; the positive samples were concentrated in this area, accounting for 42.4% of all positive samples (14/33). In summary, it is highly suspected that the outbreak is related to the wildlife trade.

Virus isolation was carried out on coronavirus-sensitive cell lines. Electron microscopy, PCR, and in-depth sequencing results have shown that the novel coronavirus has been successfully isolated from environmental samples, further confirming the seafood [market] in South China. There are a large number of new coronaviruses 2019-nCoV in urban environments.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
